04543nam a22006495i 9780231554961DE-B159720220426115627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220426t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021023384  a97802315549617 a10.7312/bari203282doi  a(DE-B1597)624602  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aDS761 4aDS761b.B37 2022 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a951/.0352231 aBarish, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLearning to Rule :bCourt Education and the Remaking of the Qing State, 1861–1912 /cDaniel Barish. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute, Columbia University00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. New Forms of Learning for a New Age of Imperial Rule, 1861– 1874 -- t2. The Malleability of Youth: Guangxu in the Classroom, 1875– 1890 -- t3. Putting Lessons Into Practice: Guangxu on the Throne, 1891– 1898 -- t4. Cixi’s Pedagogy: Female Education and Constitutional Governance, 1898– 1908 -- t5. Learning to Be a Constitutional Monarch, 1908– 1912 -- tConclusion: Emperor and Nation in Modern China -- tCharacter Glossary -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the second half of the nineteenth century, local leaders around the Qing empire attempted to rebuild in the aftermath of domestic rebellion and imperialist aggression. At the same time, the enthronement of a series of children brought the question of reconstruction into the heart of the capital. Chinese scholars, Manchu and Mongolian officials, and writers in the press all competed to have their ideas included in the education of young rulers. Each group hoped to use the power of the emperor—both his functional role within the bureaucracy and his symbolic role as an exemplar for the people—to promote reform.Daniel Barish explores debates surrounding the education of the final three Qing emperors, showing how imperial curricula became proxy battles for divergent visions of how to restabilize the country. He sheds light on the efforts of rival figures, who drew on China’s dynastic history, Manchu traditions, and the statecraft tools of imperial powers as they sought to remake the state. Barish traces how court education reflected arguments over the introduction of Western learning, the fate of the Manchu Way, the place of women in society, notions of constitutionalism, and emergent conceptions of national identity. He emphasizes how changing ideas of education intersected with a push for a renewed imperial center and national unity, helping create a model of rulership for postimperial regimes. Through the lens of the education of young emperors, Learning to Rule develops a new understanding of the late Qing era and the relationship between the monarchy and the nation in modern China.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2022) 0aEducation of princeszChinaxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966340uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/bari2032840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231554961423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231554961/original  a978-3-11-074966-3  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK